    Takes 's' â†’ becomes 'S'

So now youâ€™ve processed:

    First letter only â†’ LEFT(name, 1)

    Made it uppercase â†’ UPPER(...)

ğŸ”¸ 4. LENGTH(name)

Purpose: Returns the number of characters in the string.
âœ… Syntax:

LENGTH(string)

ğŸ’¡ In this query:

LENGTH(name) - 1

    Suppose name = 'sHaNi'

    LENGTH(name) â†’ 5

    Subtract 1 â†’ 4 (we are skipping the first letter)

ğŸ“Œ Used to determine how many characters are after the first one.
ğŸ”¸ 5. RIGHT(name, LENGTH(name) - 1)

Purpose: Extracts the last N characters from a string.
âœ… Syntax:

RIGHT(string, number_of_characters)

ğŸ’¡ In this query:

RIGHT(name, LENGTH(name) - 1)

If name = 'sHaNi':

    LENGTH(name) = 5

    RIGHT(name, 4) â†’ 'HaNi'

ğŸ“Œ This gets the rest of the name (excluding the first letter).
ğŸ”¸ 6. LOWER(...)

Purpose: Converts the input string to lowercase.
âœ… Syntax:

LOWER(string)

ğŸ’¡ In this query:

LOWER(RIGHT(name, LENGTH(name) - 1))

    Takes 'HaNi' â†’ becomes 'hani'

ğŸ“Œ Makes rest of the name lowercase to ensure consistent formatting.
âœ… Bringing it all together:

CONCAT(UPPER(LEFT(name , 1)), LOWER(RIGHT(name, LENGTH(name) - 1)))

With name = 'sHaNi':

    First letter â†’ LEFT(name, 1) = 's' â†’ UPPER() â†’ 'S'

    Remaining â†’ RIGHT(name, 4) = 'HaNi' â†’ LOWER() â†’ 'hani'

    Final â†’ 'S' + 'hani' = 'Shani'

ğŸ”¹ AS name

This is an alias. It renames the output column to name.

So your final result will be:

user_id | name
--------|-------
1       | Shani

ğŸ”¹ FROM Users

Specifies the table you are querying from.

    Users is the table that contains:

        user_id

        name

ğŸ”¹ ORDER BY user_id

Sorts the final results by user_id in ascending order.

If your table has:

